<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n25043c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n25" href="#n25043c">N25 (VI.B.15)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n25all.htm#n25043c"> 43(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> hands through stone / marriage oath <font face="wake">G</font> <font face="wake">H</font> <font face="wake">J</font></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Once granted that there was a Spirit of God dwelling within the stone, nothing could be more reasonable than that they should be used for sanctifying an <mark>oath</mark>, and particularly that most important of all oaths, the <mark>marriage covenant</mark>; and from these circles we probably derive the marriage ring. We make those who testify in our courts &lsquo;kiss the book,&rsquo; which amounts to calling God to witness. They made them <mark>join hands through or around the sanctified stone</mark>, just for the same purpose. <small> J. F. M. Ffrench, <a name="JFPF" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#JFPF"><cite title="source">Prehistoric Faith and Worship</cite></a> (1912) 30</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c14022c" href="c14all.htm#c14022c">VI.C.14:022(c)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
